title: react-bootstrap: Made props for components that wrap HTML elements extend React.HTMLProps
body:
Many of the react-bootstrap components pass props through to underlying HTML elements, for example https://github.com/react-bootstrap/react-bootstrap/blob/master/src/Tab.js#L96.

This change makes the props for those components extend React.HTMLProps, so the components can have any HTML or DOM attributes. I removed all of the attributes here that are also in HTMLProps.

I'm not sure if this is a good idea - maybe you would want to exclude attributes that don't make sense for an element, like checked on a table. But the react typings allow it, so I think react-bootstrap should as well. There are also some attributes that are set by the react-bootstrap component, like role in the Tab component, so maybe they shouldn't be in the component's props.

@vsiao would you mind looking at this?

title: HammerJS: Hammer instance is not a function
body:
Calling new Hammer(...) returns an instance of HammerManager, which the declaration file reflects. 

But that HammerManager is just an instance, it is not something which can be called with "new", because it is not a function. 

You can test this to be the case just by the following, you can run it on the HammerJS Site: http://hammerjs.github.io/. It fails with "test is not a function". 

```
var test = new Hammer(document)
test()
```

This removes that "new" call.

title: Improve GeoJSON generics
body:
GeoJSON has generics-friendly data structures, so I want to improve type accuracy.
### GeoJSON

The [Feature](http://geojson.org/geojson-spec.html#feature-objects) type has one of [Geometry Objects](http://geojson.org/geojson-spec.html#geometry-objects), so Feature can be expressed as generics.
### TurfJS

TurfJS documentation uses generics-like expression (ex. [turf-aggregate](http://turfjs.org/static/docs/module-turf_aggregate.html)). It should be implemented as generics.

cf. [API Documentation](http://turfjs.org/static/docs/)
### Polyline

Similar to turf, according to [document](https://github.com/mapbox/polyline/blob/master/API.md), 

> Takes a GeoJSON LineString feature and returns an encoded string.

so, `polyline.fromGeoJSON` needs `Feature<LineString>`.

cf. [library code](https://github.com/mapbox/polyline/blob/461a3843dfa4e0c50ca1b2d37049f491f3502648/src/polyline.js#L126-L130)

title: Allow specifying `void` for component state type parameter.

This changes the type to `{} | void` to allow this while staying stricter than `any`.

title: Joi: change any.when options - is: attribute to type any
body:
My understanding from the API documentation for the `any.when()` function is that the `is:` attribute should be of the type of the calling object rather than a schema object:
https://github.com/hapijs/joi/blob/v8.0.5/API.md#anywhenref-options

eg from the example in the API documentation:

```
const schema = {
    a: Joi.any().valid('x').when('b', { is: 5, then: Joi.valid('y'), otherwise: Joi.valid('z') }),
    b: Joi.any()
};
```

here `is:` is of type `number`

or in my case I have a `boolean` so want `is: true`

title: Fix compile errors
body:
Change line 9779 from 

``` ts
class QueryCollection<T> implements Array<T> {
```

to

``` ts
class QueryCollection<T> extends Array<T> {
```

Because I getting the **_error TS2420: Class 'QueryCollection<T>' incorrectly implements interface 'T[]'.**_
**_Property 'find' is missing in type 'QueryCollection<T>'.**_

After implementing find in .d.ts I was getting next the error about method findIndex and so on.

Simplest way to fix it, was let QueryCollection  extends Array and not implement it.

**_Typescript version**_
1.8.7

title: allow importing bootbox as a module
body:
case 2. Improvement to existing type definition.
- no new library version

Currently the definition declares a global "bootbox" assuming you'll provide the required source somehow:

```
bootbox.alert("foobar")
```

If I want to import bootbox, as seen below, I must add an additional d.ts extension to make tsc happy.

```
import * as bb from "bootbox";
```

My change allows you to import bootbox without the end user having to add additional typing files (and depending on your module loading strategy, pull in the source without need for a script tag or the like). You see this pattern in other d.ts such as [toastr](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/master/toastr/toastr.d.ts)

Once Typescript 2.0 comes out, [an improved solution](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/issues/7125#issue-134444635) will exist.

title: Q: Deferred#resolve can take a promise or value
body:
According to the documentation of Q, `deferred`s can be `resolve`d with either a value, or a promise. (https://github.com/kriskowal/q#using-deferreds)

> Note that a deferred can be resolved with a value or a promise.

This adds an overloaded definition of the `resolve` method on the `Deferred` interface, such that `resolve` can either take an optional value of type `T` or `IPromise<T>`
